				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta {{{{{\rm{G}}}}}}=\Delta {{{{{\rm{E}}}}}}+\Delta {{{{{\rm{ZPE}}}}}}-{{{{{\rm{T}}}}}}\Delta {{{{{\rm{S}}}}}}+\Delta {{{{{{\rm{G}}}}}}}_{U}+\Delta {{{{{\rm{G}}}}}}{p}_{H}+\Delta {{{{{{\rm{G}}}}}}}_{{field}}$$\end{document}where ΔE, ΔZPE and ΔS are the reaction energy, the zero-point energy contribution, and entropy change, respectively. T is temperature (set to 298.15 K). The ΔS values of gas phases H2, N2 and N2H4 were obtained from the NIST-JANAF thermodynamics table, and ΔZPE was calculated by the vibration contribution of all adsorbed species56. The free energy contributed by the electrode potential (relative to NHE) was assessed with the equation ΔGU = − neU, where n is the number of electrons transferred. ΔGpH, related to OH- in electrolyte, is the correction to the H+ free energy, which can be calculated through ΔGpH = 2.3kBT*pH, and the kB is the Boltzmann constant. ΔGfield is the free-energy correction resulted from the electrochemical double layer related to the anion and cation in electrolyte.
